t the violent overthrow of existing institutions by revolution to precede the introduction of the socialistic state. I would not, by any means, say that they are all revolutionists, but the most of them undoubtedly are. [...] The most general demands of the social democrats are the following: The state should exist exclusively for the laborers; land and capital must become collective property, and production be carried on unitedly. Private competition, in the ordinary sense of the term, is to cease.|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last1=Engels|first1=Friedrich|last2=Marx|first2=Karl|year=1848|url=https://www.marxists.org/archive/marx/works/1848/communist-manifesto/|title=The Communist Manifesto|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=Engels|first=Friedrich|year=2004|title=Collected Works|volume=50|location=New York|publisher=International Publishers|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=Esping-Andersen|first=G\u00f8sta|year=1985|title=Politics Against Markets: The Social Democratic Road to Power|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=9780691654188|jstor=j.ctt1m322zp|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=Esping-Andersen|first=G\u00f8sta|year=1991|title=The Three Worlds of Welfare Capitalism|location=Princeton, New Jersey|publisher=Princeton University Press|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=F\u00e9dorovski|first=Vladimir|year=2007|chapter=Situations VII|title=Le Fant\u00f4me de Staline|trans-title=The Ghost of Stalin|language=French|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Tony|year=2003|title=After the New Social Democracy: Social Welfare for the Twenty-First Century|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=9780719064777|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last1=Fog|first1=Mogens|last2=Kragh|first2=Jens|last3=Larsen|first3=Aksel|last4=Moltke|first4=Kai|last5=Petersen|first5=Gert|year=1977|title=Folkesocialisme|language=Danish|publisher=SP Forl|ref=harv}}\n: {{cite book|last=Foley|first=Michael|year=1994|title=Ideas that Shape Politics|publisher=Manchester University Press|page=23|isbn=978-0-719