\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = Welcome to the Real World\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = Don't Say It's Over\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n\nIn the 1990s, \"Word Up!\" was first covered by Scottish [[hard rock]] band [[Gun (band)|Gun]], whose version carried a harder, more rock-oriented sound, including a guitar solo.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Taken from their album ''[[Swagger (Gun album)|Swagger]]'', it was released on July 1, 1994, and reached number 8 in the UK singles chart.<ref name=\"UK\"/> Two versions of the CD single were released in the UK, each carrying different cover art and different tracks.<ref>{{cite web|title= Gun \u2013 Word Up CD 1 |publisher= Matt's CD Singles |url= http://www.mattscdsingles.com/acatalog/Online_Catalogue_Gun_112.html#a20594 |accessdate= February 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1994)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|41|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n|Belgium ([[VRT Top 30]] Flanders)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/3322 |title= Word Up \u2013 GUN |work= VRT |publisher= Top30-2.radio2.be |language= Dutch |accessdate= July 31, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120409063716/http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/3322 |archivedate= April 9, 2012 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|46|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|32|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|songid=13036|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|17|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|21|artist=Gun (1994) \u2013 Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|14|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|39|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|8|date=July 9, 1994|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013|refname=\"UK\"}}\n|}\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Mel B version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = Wordupcover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mel B|Melanie G]]\n| album      = [[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me#Soundtrack|Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me: Music from the Motion Picture]]\n| B-side     = Sophisticated Lady\n| released   = June 28, 1999\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[12\" single|12\"]]\n* [[CD single|CD]]\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:25 {{small|(radio edit)}}<br>5:23 {{small|(single version)}}\n| label      = {{flat list|\n*[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n*[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n}}\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n*Blackmon\n*Jenkins\n}}\n| producer   = [[Timbaland]]\n| prev_title = [[I Want You Back (Mel B song)|I Want You Back]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[Tell Me (Mel B song)|Tell Me]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|AhUi_e36H4U|\"Word Up\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Word Up!'''\" was later covered by [[Mel B]] of the [[Spice Girls]] (known as '''Melanie G''' at that time) from the film soundtrack ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me (soundtrack)|Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]''. It was released on June 28, 1999 and peaked at number 13 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. The single was also included on the Japanese edition of her album ''[[Hot (Mel B album)|Hot]]''.\n\n===Format and track listing===\n*;Digital download EP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/word-up-single/id724858089|title=Word Up \u2013 EP by Melanie G|publisher=[[iTunes]]}}</ref>\n#\"Word Up\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:23\n#\"Sophisticated Lady\" <small>(featuring [[Emma Bunton]] & [[Dexter (singer)|Dexter]])</small> \u2013 2:44\n#\"Word Up\" ([[Timbaland|Tim]]'s Dance Mix) \u2013 5:31\n\n===Chart performance===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1999)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/indici/per_interprete/am.htm |title= Indice per Interprete: M |work= HitParadeItalia |publisher= Creative Commons |language= Italian |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|34\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|86|artist=Melanie G|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|13|date=July 10, 1999|artist=Melanie G|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|}\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Korn version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = Word_Up!.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Korn]]\n| album      = [[Greatest Hits, Volume 1 (Korn album)|Greatest Hits, Vol. 1]]\n| released   = November 16, 2004\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[7\" single]]\n* [[12\" single]]\n* CD single\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 2:53\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Larry Blackmon]], Tomi Jenkins\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jonathan Davis]]\n* [[Korn]]\n* [[Toby Wright]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Everything I've Known]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Another Brick in the Wall#Korn version|Another Brick in the Wall, Pts. 1\u20133]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n\"'''Word Up!'''\" by American [[nu metal]] band [[Korn]] is a cover of the Cameo song.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Its musical arrangements are similar to that of the cover version by [[Gun (band)|Gun]], except it is played in a lower sounding 7 string guitar tuning instead of the standard E.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} \"Word Up!\" was the first track featured on Korn's 2004 [[retrospective album]], ''[[Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 (Korn album)|Greatest Hits, Volume 1]]'', and was one of two new tracks along with [[Pink Floyd]]'s \"[[Another Brick in the Wall]]\" that was exclusive to the album (the \"Word Up!\" CD single also featured a live performance of the latter).\n\n=== Background and release ===\nIt was released as the album's first single in July 2004, and received heavy airplay on alternative radio at its time of release, peaking in the top 20 of both ''Billboard'' charts,<ref name=\"awards2\"/> whilst making a respectable impression on the mainstream charts of other countries, including Australia (where it debuted at number 28),<ref name=\"AUS\"/> and Germany (number 46).<ref name=\"GER\"/> It is the only Korn single to be sent out to [[Top 40 (radio format)|Top 40]] radio stations, notably receiving airplay on New York City's [[WHTZ|Z-100]], the largest Top 40 station in the US. Lead singer [[Jonathan Davis]] has said of the band's decision to include the song on their greatest hits, \"We've been doing 'Word Up!' for years as a sound-check song\u2014not the full version, just messing around with the riff.\"<ref>[http://v4.korn-locker.com/modules.php?name=Lyrics&file=show&album=7&lyric=0701] {{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Chart performance ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2004)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|28|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013|refname=\"AUS\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|58|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|9|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n|Brazil ([[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos|ABPD]])<ref name=\"Brazil\">{{cite web |url = http://asdfg-menezes.org/bookBR.pdf |title = Brazil |work = ABPD |date = October 6, 2001 |accessdate = April 1, 2014 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|75\n|-\n|Canada Rock Top 30 ([[Radio & Records]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2004/RR-2004-11-19.pdf|title=RR Canada Rock Top 30|p=58|accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|46|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|songid=6339|accessdate=July 31, 2013|refname=\"GER\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|15|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|47|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardbubbling100|23|artist=Korn|song=Word Up|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}\n|-\n|US [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\">{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-vol-1-mw0000301944/awards |title= Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 awards at Allmusic |work= [[AllMusic]] |publisher= [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|US [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|}\n{{-}}\n\n==Jan Delay version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| border     = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jan Delay]]\n| album      = Mercedes-Dance-Live\n| released   = 2007\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:06\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n* Im- und Export Hanburg-City\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Larry Blackmon]]|Tomi Jenkins|Das Bo|[[Jan Delay|Jan Ei\u00dffeldt]]|Kaspar Wiens}}\n| producer   = Jan Delay\n| prev_title = Im Arsch\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = Alles bleibt anders\n| next_year  = 2008\n}}\nIn 2007 German singer [[Jan Delay]] recorded a [[mashup (music)|mashup]] of the music from \"Word Up!\" with the lyrics of Das Bo's \"T\u00fcrlich, T\u00fcrlich (Sicher, Dicker)\". The new song was titled \"T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)\" and was a hit in German-speaking countries.\n\n===Charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2007)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|49|artist=Jan Delay|song=T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|31|artist=Jan Delay|song=T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)|songid=251198}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|84|artist=Jan Delay|song=T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)}}\n|}\n{{-}}\n\n==Little Mix version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = Little_Mix_Word_Up.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Little Mix]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|03|16}}\n| format     = \n* [[CD single]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=29}}\n| label      = \n* [[Syco Music|Syco]]\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = \n* [[Larry Blackmon]]\n* Tomi Jenkins\n| producer   =\n* [[TMS (production team)|TMS]]\n* [[Maegan Cottone]]\n| prev_title = [[Little Me (song)|Little Me]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Salute (song)|Salute]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|1zk0ToEA8sY|\"Word Up!\"}}}}\n}}\n\nBritish girl group [[Little Mix]] covered the song for [[Sport Relief#Sport Relief 2014|''Sport Relief'' 2014]]. It was released digitally on March 16, 2014, followed by a physical release the following day, which was only available to purchase from [[Sainsbury's]].<ref name=\"release1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a544605/little-mix-to-release-2014-sport-relief-single-word-up.html |title=Little Mix to release 2014 Sport Relief single 'Word Up'|work=Digital Spy |date=January 16, 2014 |accessdate=2014-01-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Background and release ===\nLittle Mix first announced the single on January 16, 2014, through their official Twitter.<ref name=\"release1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10578772/Little-Mix-to-cover-Word-Up-as-Sport-Relief-single.html|title=Little Mix to cover Word Up as Sport Relief single|work=The Daily Tuelegraph|accessdate=January 17, 2014|first=Charlotte|last=Runcie}}</ref> The song was first played on [[BBC Radio 1]] on January 20, 2014, during [[Nick Grimshaw]]'s Breakfast show.<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a545467/little-mix-premiere-sport-relief-single-word-up-listen.html|title=Little Mix premiere Sport Relief single 'Word Up' \u2013 listen|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=January 21, 2014|author=Lewis Corner}}</ref>\n\nThe cover art of the single was revealed on January 24, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a546330/little-mix-reveal-sport-relief-single-word-up-artwork.html|title=Little Mix reveal Sport Relief single 'Word Up' artwork|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=January 24, 2014|first=Robert|last=Copsey}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nThe song received rather positive reviews with the ''Popjustice'' ranking it as third for the best version of the song and third for the best [[Sport Relief#Sport Relief singles|Sport Relief single]] and gave the song 7 out of 10 stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popjustice.com/songs/little-mix-word-up/|title=Little Mix \u2013 'Word Up!'|work=Popjustice|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref> Kevin Kevinpod of DirectLyrics said that \"[Little Mix's] harmonies are spot-on, and the whole record is pure fire.\" and that the song is a chance of the band getting a number one hit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.directlyrics.com/new-music-little-mix-word-up-full-audio-review-news.html|title=New Music: Little Mix \u2013 \"Word Up\" [Full Audio + Review]|work=DirectLyrics|accessdate=January 21, 2014|last=Kevinpod|first=Kevin}}</ref> Its production was also likened to [[Janet Jackson]]'s single \"[[Black Cat (song)|Black Cat]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://renownedforsound.com/index.php/single-review-little-mix-word-up/|title=Renowned for Sound \u2013 Single Review: Little Mix \u2013 'Word Up'|work=Lee, Andrew|publisher=[[Renowned for Sound]]|date=March 16, 2014|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Music video ===\nThe shooting for the music video started in early February 2014. The band posted an exclusive picture from the video on February 25, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LittleMixOfficial/photos/a.131494490285598.18956.126963587405355/461866543915056/?type=1&theater|title=EXCLUSIVE pic from the video|accessdate=February 25, 2014|publisher=Facebook}}</ref> The video was first shown on the Chart Show TV on February 28, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.josepvinaixa.com/blog/little-mix-word-up-video-premiere/|title=Little Mix \"Word Up!\" (Video Premiere)|work=Ultimate Music|accessdate=March 2, 2014|last=Vinaixa|first=Josep|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305013501/http://www.josepvinaixa.com/blog/little-mix-word-up-video-premiere/|archive-date=March 5, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and was posted on [[Vevo]] on March 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a554994/little-mix-unveil-star-studded-video-for-sport-relief-single-word-up.html|title=Little Mix unveil star-studded video for Sport Relief single 'Word Up'|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=March 3, 2014|last=Copsey|first=Robert}}</ref> It features celebrity cameos from [[Nick Grimshaw]], [[Louie Spence]], [[Louis Smith (gymnast)|Louis Smith]], [[Arlene Phillips]], [[Melanie C]] and [[Chris Barrie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/little-mix/news/little-mix-joined-by-famous-faces-in-word-up-sport-relief-video|title=Little Mix Joined By Famous Faces In 'Word Up' Sport Relief Video|work=MTV|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe video starts off with the band in a changing room of a gym. As they walk out of the changing room, Jade tries to pick up a [[barbell]] pretending that she cannot lift it but then she lifts it up and walks away carrying it. Perrie then walks along four women who are working out while Jade is on a [[stationary bicycle]] among three other women, following the instructions of a trainer. With the bicycle, Jade starts going forward with the rest following her at the back.\n\nThe scene then switches to a court with the band exercising and dancing the same time along with other people while singing the chorus of the song. Afterwards, Leigh-Anne is stood in front of some athletes with one using her as a barbell at the end of her part. Jesy continues with her part while dancing in front of two men working out on [[treadmill]]s and fall off them after some time. During the chorus, the scene changes again to the court with the owner (Barrie, who had previously played a gym manager in BBC sitcom ''[[The Brittas Empire]]'') of the gym seeing the girls and the rest dancing and runs upset out of his office. As he is going down to the court, he sees the athletes in the swimming pool shaping out the title of the song. When he reaches the court, he starts dancing with them.\n\n=== Track listings ===\n;Digital download<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/word-up!-single/id795609578|title = Word Up! \u2013 Single|date = March 14, 2014|accessdate = |website = iTunes|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n#\"Word Up!\" \u2013 3:26\n\n;Digital remixes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Word-Up-Remixes-Little-Mix/dp/B00IK5AG7O/ref=sr_1_2?s=dmusic&ie=UTF8&qid=1394923563&sr=1-2&keywords=little+mix+word+up |title=Word Up! (Remixes): Little Mix: Amazon.co.uk: MP3 Downloads |work=Amazon.co.uk}}</ref>\n#\"Word Up!\" (The Alias Radio Edit) \u2013 3:33\n#\"Word Up!\" (Extended Mix) \u2013 4:59\n#\"Word Up!\" (Instrumental) \u2013 3:05\n\n;CD single<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Word-Up-Single-Little-Mix/dp/B00J1TK600/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1395070624&sr=8-5&keywords=Little+mix+word+up|title=Word Up! [CD single]: Amazon.co.uk: Music|work=Amazon.co.uk}}</ref>\n#\"Word Up!\" \u2013 3:26\n#\"Word Up!\" (The Alias Radio Edit) \u2013 3:33\n#\"Word Up!\" (Extended Mix) \u2013 4:59\n#\"Word Up!\" (Instrumental) \u2013 3:05\n\n=== Chart performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! Chart (2014)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|45|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|65|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Czech Republic|92|year=2014|week=14}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|38|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|107|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Irish|13|year=2014|week=12}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardjapanhot100|71|artist=Little Mix|song=Word Up}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|8|date=20140329}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|6|date=20140329}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Release history ===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n!scope=\"col\"| Region\n!scope=\"col\"| Date\n!scope=\"col\"| Format\n!scope=\"col\"| Label\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"|United Kingdom\n|March 16, 2014\n|[[Music download|Digital download]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Syco Music|Syco]]\n|-\n|March 17, 2014\n|CD single (Exclusive to [[Sainsbury's]])\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|cameo|word-up}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Cameo}}\n{{Gun (band)}}\n{{Melanie B}}\n{{Korn}}\n{{Little Mix}}\n\n[[Category:1986 singles]]\n[[Category:1994 singles]]\n[[Category:1999 singles]]\n[[Category:2004 singles]]\n[[Category:2014 singles]]\n[[Category:Cameo (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Korn songs]]\n[[Category:Mel B songs]]\n[[Category:Little Mix songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Timbaland]]\n[[Category:Songs written for films]]\n[[Category:1986 songs]]\n[[Category:Mercury Records singles]]\n[[Category:Gun (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Larry Blackmon]]\n\n[[fr:Word Up!]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1986 single by Cameo}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = WordUpCameo.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cameo (band)|Cameo]]\n| album      = [[Word Up! (album)|Word Up!]]\n| B-side     = Urban Warrior\n| released   = May 27, 1986\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[7\" single]]\n* [[12\" single]]\n* [[CD single]]\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Funk]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Rock: The Rough Guide|authors=Jonathan Buckley, Mark Ellingham|editor=Rough Guides Ltd|year=1996|isbn=978-1858282015|url=https://archive.org/details/rockroughguide00buck}} \"\"Word Up\" was funk's last stand before it was completely swallowed up by hip-hop culture.\"</ref>\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Third Coast: Outkast, Timbaland, and How Hip-Hop Became a Southern Thing|author=Roni Sarig|editor=Da Capo Press|year=2007|isbn=978-0306814303|page=[https://archive.org/details/thirdcoastoutkas00sari/page/100 100]|url=https://archive.org/details/thirdcoastoutkas00sari/page/100}} \"With number-one R&B singles like 1984's \"She's Strange\" and 1986's \"Word Up\"\u2014released on Cameo's Atlanta Artists label\u2014the city found its first major urban act of the hip-hop era.\"</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 4:21\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Atlanta Artists Records|Atlanta Artists]]\n* [[Mercury Records|Mercury]]\n* [[PolyGram]]}}\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n* [[Larry Blackmon]]\n* Tomi Jenkins\n}}\n| producer   = Larry Blackmon\n| prev_title = Single Life\n| prev_year  = 1985\n| next_title = [[Candy (Cameo song)|Candy]]\n| next_year  = 1986\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{Youtube|MZjAantupsA|\"Word Up\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Word Up!'''\" is a [[funk]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] song originally recorded by American funk band [[Cameo (band)|Cameo]] in 1986. The song was written by band members [[Larry Blackmon]] and Tomi Jenkins. Its frequent airing on American dance, R&B, and contemporary hit radio, as well as its [[MTV]] music video (in which [[LeVar Burton]] appears as a police detective trying to arrest the band),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/news/cameos-got-word|title=Cameo's Got The Word|date=September 28, 2011|publisher=grammy.com|accessdate=September 2, 2017}}</ref> helped the single become the band's best known hit.\n\n==Release and reception==\nFrom the album ''[[Word Up! (album)|Word Up!]]'', \"Word Up!\" was Cameo's first US [[Top 40]] hit, peaking at number 6 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and spending three weeks at number 1 on the US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|R&B chart]]<ref>{{cite book|title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942\u20132004 |author= [[Joel Whitburn]] |year= 2004 |publisher= Record Research |page= 98}}</ref> and one week at number 1 on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Singles]] chart. In the [[UK Singles Chart|UK]], it spent 10 weeks in the top 40, peaking at number 3 on September 21, 1986.\n\nBesides being a commercial success, the track also earned critical acclaim from several publications. \"Word Up!\" won Cameo the [[Soul Train Music Award for Best R&B/Soul Single, Group, Band or Duo|Soul Train Music Award for Best R&B/Soul Single]] as well as the [[NME Award]] for Best Dance Record. Like the band's previous single \"Single Life\", \"Word Up!\" features a reference to the opening notes of [[Ennio Morricone]]'s theme to ''[[The Good, the Bad and the Ugly (theme)|The Good, the Bad and the Ugly]]''.\n\n\"Word Up\" was a [[colloquialism]], popular in [[New York City]] and other US urban areas, that acted as an affirmation of what was said\u2009\u2014\u2009a kind of a more-hip \"You Bet.\"\n\nBlackmon said of the song:\n<blockquote>It just sounded good, and it was before its time. You can play 'Word Up' anyplace anywhere, and someone is going to be grooving and bobbing their head. Our sound was unique, as well. I haven\u2019t heard another one like it, and we probably won\u2019t hear another one like it in the future. It was that significant for us.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/robin-leach/cameo-frontman-larry-blackmon-word-was-music-its-time-paying-tribute-prince|title=Cameo frontman Larry Blackmon: \u2018Word Up\u2019 was music before its time|first=Robin |last=Leach |date=July 29, 2016 |newspaper=reviewjournal.com |accessdate=October 16, 2016}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Impact and legacy==\n''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' listed the song number 54 in their ''The 100 best party songs'' list in 2018.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The 100 best party songs|magazine=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|url=https://www.timeout.com/london/music/best-party-songs|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (1986\u201387)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book |first=David |last=Kent |authorlink=David Kent (historian) |title=Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992 |page=53 |publisher=Australian Chart Books |location=[[St Ives, New South Wales]], Australia |date=1993 |isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|10|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|8|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n|Belgium ([[VRT Top 30]] Flanders)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/1279 |title= Word Up \u2013 CAMEO |work= VRT |publisher= Top30-2.radio2.be |language= Dutch |accessdate= July 31, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120409063716/http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/1279 |archivedate= April 9, 2012 |df= mdy-all }} Hoogste notering in de top 30 : 8</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|8\n|-\n|Canada ([[RPM (magazine)|''RPM'' 100 Singles]])<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0756&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |title= Top Singles \u2013 Volume 45, No. 13, December 20, 1986 |publisher= Library and Archives Canada |accessdate= July 31, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140224000501/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.0756&type=1&interval=20&PHPSESSID=u9874ano8k0c5b6bkp4r8qrbp3 |archive-date= February 24, 2014 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|Europe ([[European Hot 100 Singles|Pan-European Charts]])<ref>{{cite journal |title= Billboard 15 November 1986 |editor= Danyel Smith |publisher= Nielsen Business Media, Inc. |year= 1986 |issn= 0006-2510 |url= https://books.google.com/?id=UCQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA77&dq=%22word+up+cameo%22+%22pan+european+charts%22#v=onepage&q=%22word%20up%20cameo%22%20%22pan%20european%20charts%22&f=false |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|14\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|3|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up!|songid=1522|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|8|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/hp_yends/hpe1987.htm |title= I singoli pi\u00f9 venduti del 1987 |work= HitParadeItalia |publisher= Creative Commons |language= Italian |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}<br>47. Word up \u2013 Cameo [#6, 1986/87]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|10|artist=Cameo \u2013 Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|9|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|1|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|13|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|3|date=September 27, 1986|artist=Cameo|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/word-up%21-mw0000193157/awards |title= Word Up! awards at Allmusic |work= [[AllMusic]] |publisher= [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n|US [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]]<ref name=\"awards\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|US [[Dance/Electronic Singles Sales|Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]]<ref name=\"awards\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Black Singles]]<ref name=\"awards\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Chart (1986)\n! Rank\n|-\n| UK Singles ([[Gallup (company)|Gallup]])<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Top 100 Singles |magazine=[[Music Week]] |page=24 |date=24 January 1987}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 36\n|-\n| US ''Billboard'' Pop Singles<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Top Pop Singles |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |date=December 27, 1986}} (\"1986: The Year in Music and Video\" supplement, p. Y-21)</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 68\n|-\n! Chart (1987)\n! Rank\n|-\n| German Singles (Offizielle Deutsche Charts)<ref>{{cite web |title=Top 100 Single \u2013 Jahrescharts 1987 |url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1987 |accessdate=October 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 67\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Gun version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = GunWordUp.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Gun (band)|Gun]]\n| album      = [[Swagger (Gun album)|Swagger]]\n| released   = July 1, 1994\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[12\" single]]\n* CD single\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hard rock]]\n| length     = 4:13\n| label      = [[A&M Records|A&M]]\n| writer     = [[Larry Blackmon]], Tomi Jenkins\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = Welcome to the Real World\n| prev_year  = 1992\n| next_title = Don't Say It's Over\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n\nIn the 1990s, \"Word Up!\" was first covered by Scottish [[hard rock]] band [[Gun (band)|Gun]], whose version carried a harder, more rock-oriented sound, including a guitar solo.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Taken from their album ''[[Swagger (Gun album)|Swagger]]'', it was released on July 1, 1994, and reached number 8 in the UK singles chart.<ref name=\"UK\"/> Two versions of the CD single were released in the UK, each carrying different cover art and different tracks.<ref>{{cite web|title= Gun \u2013 Word Up CD 1 |publisher= Matt's CD Singles |url= http://www.mattscdsingles.com/acatalog/Online_Catalogue_Gun_112.html#a20594 |accessdate= February 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Chart performance===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1994)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|41|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n|Belgium ([[VRT Top 30]] Flanders)<ref>{{cite web |url= http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/3322 |title= Word Up \u2013 GUN |work= VRT |publisher= Top30-2.radio2.be |language= Dutch |accessdate= July 31, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120409063716/http://top30-2.radio2.be/#/song-info/3322 |archivedate= April 9, 2012 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|24\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|46|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|32|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|songid=13036|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|17|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 9, 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|21|artist=Gun (1994) \u2013 Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|14|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|39|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|8|date=July 9, 1994|artist=Gun|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013|refname=\"UK\"}}\n|}\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Mel B version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = Wordupcover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Mel B|Melanie G]]\n| album      = [[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me#Soundtrack|Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me: Music from the Motion Picture]]\n| B-side     = Sophisticated Lady\n| released   = June 28, 1999\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[12\" single|12\"]]\n* [[CD single|CD]]\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:25 {{small|(radio edit)}}<br>5:23 {{small|(single version)}}\n| label      = {{flat list|\n*[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n*[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n}}\n| writer     = {{flat list|\n*Blackmon\n*Jenkins\n}}\n| producer   = [[Timbaland]]\n| prev_title = [[I Want You Back (Mel B song)|I Want You Back]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[Tell Me (Mel B song)|Tell Me]]\n| next_year  = 2000\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|AhUi_e36H4U|\"Word Up\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Word Up!'''\" was later covered by [[Mel B]] of the [[Spice Girls]] (known as '''Melanie G''' at that time) from the film soundtrack ''[[Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me (soundtrack)|Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me]]''. It was released on June 28, 1999 and peaked at number 13 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. The single was also included on the Japanese edition of her album ''[[Hot (Mel B album)|Hot]]''.\n\n===Format and track listing===\n*;Digital download EP<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/in/album/word-up-single/id724858089|title=Word Up \u2013 EP by Melanie G|publisher=[[iTunes]]}}</ref>\n#\"Word Up\" (Radio Edit) \u2013 3:23\n#\"Sophisticated Lady\" <small>(featuring [[Emma Bunton]] & [[Dexter (singer)|Dexter]])</small> \u2013 2:44\n#\"Word Up\" ([[Timbaland|Tim]]'s Dance Mix) \u2013 5:31\n\n===Chart performance===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1999)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n|Italy ([[Federazione Industria Musicale Italiana|FIMI]])<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.hitparadeitalia.it/indici/per_interprete/am.htm |title= Indice per Interprete: M |work= HitParadeItalia |publisher= Creative Commons |language= Italian |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|34\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|86|artist=Melanie G|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|13|date=July 10, 1999|artist=Melanie G|song=Word Up|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|}\n\n{{-}}\n\n==Korn version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = Word_Up!.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Korn]]\n| album      = [[Greatest Hits, Volume 1 (Korn album)|Greatest Hits, Vol. 1]]\n| released   = November 16, 2004\n| format     = {{flatlist|\n* [[7\" single]]\n* [[12\" single]]\n* CD single\n}}\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n| length     = 2:53\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = [[Larry Blackmon]], Tomi Jenkins\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Jonathan Davis]]\n* [[Korn]]\n* [[Toby Wright]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Everything I've Known]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Another Brick in the Wall#Korn version|Another Brick in the Wall, Pts. 1\u20133]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n\n\"'''Word Up!'''\" by American [[nu metal]] band [[Korn]] is a cover of the Cameo song.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}} Its musical arrangements are similar to that of the cover version by [[Gun (band)|Gun]], except it is played in a lower sounding 7 string guitar tuning instead of the standard E.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} \"Word Up!\" was the first track featured on Korn's 2004 [[retrospective album]], ''[[Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 (Korn album)|Greatest Hits, Volume 1]]'', and was one of two new tracks along with [[Pink Floyd]]'s \"[[Another Brick in the Wall]]\" that was exclusive to the album (the \"Word Up!\" CD single also featured a live performance of the latter).\n\n=== Background and release ===\nIt was released as the album's first single in July 2004, and received heavy airplay on alternative radio at its time of release, peaking in the top 20 of both ''Billboard'' charts,<ref name=\"awards2\"/> whilst making a respectable impression on the mainstream charts of other countries, including Australia (where it debuted at number 28),<ref name=\"AUS\"/> and Germany (number 46).<ref name=\"GER\"/> It is the only Korn single to be sent out to [[Top 40 (radio format)|Top 40]] radio stations, notably receiving airplay on New York City's [[WHTZ|Z-100]], the largest Top 40 station in the US. Lead singer [[Jonathan Davis]] has said of the band's decision to include the song on their greatest hits, \"We've been doing 'Word Up!' for years as a sound-check song\u2014not the full version, just messing around with the riff.\"<ref>[http://v4.korn-locker.com/modules.php?name=Lyrics&file=show&album=7&lyric=0701] {{dead link|date=March 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Chart performance ===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (2004)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|28|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013|refname=\"AUS\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|58|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Tip|9|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n|Brazil ([[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos|ABPD]])<ref name=\"Brazil\">{{cite web |url = http://asdfg-menezes.org/bookBR.pdf |title = Brazil |work = ABPD |date = October 6, 2001 |accessdate = April 1, 2014 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|75\n|-\n|Canada Rock Top 30 ([[Radio & Records]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/2000s/2004/RR-2004-11-19.pdf|title=RR Canada Rock Top 30|p=58|accessdate=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|46|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|songid=6339|accessdate=July 31, 2013|refname=\"GER\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Norway|15|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|47|artist=Korn|song=Word Up!|accessdate=July 31, 2013}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardbubbling100|23|artist=Korn|song=Word Up|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}\n|-\n|US [[Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\">{{cite web|url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/greatest-hits-vol-1-mw0000301944/awards |title= Greatest Hits, Vol. 1 awards at Allmusic |work= [[AllMusic]] |publisher= [[Rovi Corporation]] |accessdate= July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|US [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|}\n{{-}}\n\n==Jan Delay version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| border     = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Jan Delay]]\n| album      = Mercedes-Dance-Live\n| released   = 2007\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = \n| length     = 3:06\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n* Im- und Export Hanburg-City\n* [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]\n}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Larry Blackmon]]|Tomi Jenkins|Das Bo|[[Jan Delay|Jan Ei\u00dffeldt]]|Kaspar Wiens}}\n| producer   = Jan Delay\n| prev_title = Im Arsch\n| prev_year  = 2007\n| next_title = Alles bleibt anders\n| next_year  = 2008\n}}\nIn 2007 German singer [[Jan Delay]] recorded a [[mashup (music)|mashup]] of the music from \"Word Up!\" with the lyrics of Das Bo's \"T\u00fcrlich, T\u00fcrlich (Sicher, Dicker)\". The new song was titled \"T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)\" and was a hit in German-speaking countries.\n\n===Charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2007)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|49|artist=Jan Delay|song=T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|31|artist=Jan Delay|song=T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)|songid=251198}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|84|artist=Jan Delay|song=T\u00fcrlich T\u00fcrlich (Word Up)}}\n|}\n{{-}}\n\n==Little Mix version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Word Up!\n| cover      = Little_Mix_Word_Up.png\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Little Mix]]\n| album      =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|03|16}}\n| format     = \n* [[CD single]]\n* [[Music download|digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Dance-pop]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=29}}\n| label      = \n* [[Syco Music|Syco]]\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = \n* [[Larry Blackmon]]\n* Tomi Jenkins\n| producer   =\n* [[TMS (production team)|TMS]]\n* [[Maegan Cottone]]\n| prev_title = [[Little Me (song)|Little Me]]\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Salute (song)|Salute]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|1zk0ToEA8sY|\"Word Up!\"}}}}\n}}\n\nBritish girl group [[Little Mix]] covered the song for [[Sport Relief#Sport Relief 2014|''Sport Relief'' 2014]]. It was released digitally on March 16, 2014, followed by a physical release the following day, which was only available to purchase from [[Sainsbury's]].<ref name=\"release1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a544605/little-mix-to-release-2014-sport-relief-single-word-up.html |title=Little Mix to release 2014 Sport Relief single 'Word Up'|work=Digital Spy |date=January 16, 2014 |accessdate=2014-01-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Background and release ===\nLittle Mix first announced the single on January 16, 2014, through their official Twitter.<ref name=\"release1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10578772/Little-Mix-to-cover-Word-Up-as-Sport-Relief-single.html|title=Little Mix to cover Word Up as Sport Relief single|work=The Daily Tuelegraph|accessdate=January 17, 2014|first=Charlotte|last=Runcie}}</ref> The song was first played on [[BBC Radio 1]] on January 20, 2014, during [[Nick Grimshaw]]'s Breakfast show.<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a545467/little-mix-premiere-sport-relief-single-word-up-listen.html|title=Little Mix premiere Sport Relief single 'Word Up' \u2013 listen|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=January 21, 2014|author=Lewis Corner}}</ref>\n\nThe cover art of the single was revealed on January 24, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a546330/little-mix-reveal-sport-relief-single-word-up-artwork.html|title=Little Mix reveal Sport Relief single 'Word Up' artwork|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=January 24, 2014|first=Robert|last=Copsey}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical reception ===\nThe song received rather positive reviews with the ''Popjustice'' ranking it as third for the best version of the song and third for the best [[Sport Relief#Sport Relief singles|Sport Relief single]] and gave the song 7 out of 10 stars.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.popjustice.com/songs/little-mix-word-up/|title=Little Mix \u2013 'Word Up!'|work=Popjustice|accessdate=March 16, 2014}}</ref> Kevin Kevinpod of DirectLyrics said that \"[Little Mix's] harmonies are spot-on, and the whole record is pure fire.\" and that the song is a chance of the band getting a number one hit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.directlyrics.com/new-music-little-mix-word-up-full-audio-review-news.html|title=New Music: Little Mix \u2013 \"Word Up\" [Full Audio + Review]|work=DirectLyrics|accessdate=January 21, 2014|last=Kevinpod|first=Kevin}}</ref> Its production was also likened to [[Janet Jackson]]'s single \"[[Black Cat (song)|Black Cat]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://renownedforsound.com/index.php/single-review-little-mix-word-up/|title=Renowned for Sound \u2013 Single Review: Little Mix \u2013 'Word Up'|work=Lee, Andrew|publisher=[[Renowned for Sound]]|date=March 16, 2014|accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Music video ===\nThe shooting for the music video started in early February 2014. The band posted an exclusive picture from the video on February 25, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LittleMixOfficial/photos/a.131494490285598.18956.126963587405355/461866543915056/?type=1&theater|title=EXCLUSIVE pic from the video|accessdate=February 25, 2014|publisher=Facebook}}</ref> The video was first shown on the Chart Show TV on February 28, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.josepvinaixa.com/blog/little-mix-word-up-video-premiere/|title=Little Mix \"Word Up!\" (Video Premiere)|work=Ultimate Music|accessdate=March 2, 2014|last=Vinaixa|first=Josep|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140305013501/http://www.josepvinaixa.com/blog/little-mix-word-up-video-premiere/|archive-date=March 5, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and was posted on [[Vevo]] on March 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a554994/little-mix-unveil-star-studded-video-for-sport-relief-single-word-up.html|title=Little Mix unveil star-studded video for Sport Relief single 'Word Up'|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=March 3, 2014|last=Copsey|first=Robert}}</ref> It features celebrity cameos from [[Nick Grimshaw]], [[Louie Spence]], [[Louis Smith (gymnast)|Louis Smith]], [[Arlene Phillips]], [[Melanie C]] and [[Chris Barrie]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/little-mix/news/little-mix-joined-by-famous-faces-in-word-up-sport-relief-video|title=Little Mix Joined By Famous Faces In 'Word Up' Sport Relief Video|work=MTV|accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe video starts off with the band in a changing room of a gym. As they walk out of the changing room, Jade tries to pick up a [[barbell]] pretending that she cannot lift it but then she lifts it up and walks away carrying it. Perrie then walks along four women who are working out while Jade is on a [[stationary bicycle]] among three other women, following the instructions of a trainer. With the bicycle, Jade starts going forward with the rest following her at the back.\n\nThe scene then switches to a court with the band exercising and dancing the same time along with other people while singing the chorus of the song. Afterwards, Leigh-Anne is stood in front of some athletes with one using her as a barbell at the end of her part. Jesy continues with her part while dancing in front of two men working out on [[treadmill]]s and fall off them after some time. During the chorus, the scene changes again to the court with the owner (Barrie, who had previously played a gym manager in BBC sitcom [[The Brittas Empire]]) of the gym seeing the girls and the rest dancing and runs upset out of his office. As he is going down to the court, he sees the athletes in the swimming pool shaping out the title of the song. When he reaches the court, he starts dancing with them.\n\n=== Track listings ===\n;Digital download<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/word-up!-single/id795609578|title = Word Up! \u2013 Single|date = March 14, 2014|accessdate = |website = iTunes|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n#\"Word Up!\" \u2013 3:26\n\n;Digital remixes<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Word-Up-Remixes-Little-Mix/dp/B00IK5AG7O/ref=sr_1_2?s=dmusic&ie=UTF8&qid=1394923563&sr=1-2&keywords=little+mix+word+up |title=Word Up! (Remixes): Little Mix: Amazon.co.uk: MP3 Downloads |work=Amazon.co.uk}}</ref>\n#\"Word Up!\" (The Alias Radio Edit) \u2013 3:33\n#\"Word Up!\" (Extended Mix) \u2013 4:59\n#\"Word Up!\" (Instrumental) \u2013 3:05\n\n;CD single<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Word-Up-Single-Little-Mix/dp/B00J1TK600/ref=sr_1_5?ie=UTF8&qid=1395070624&sr=8-5&keywords=Little+mix+word+up|title=Word Up! [CD single]: Amazon.co.uk: Music|work=Amazon.co.uk}}</ref>\n#\"Word Up!\" \u2013 3:26\n#\"Word Up!\" (The Alias Radio Edit) \u2013 3:33\n#\"Word Up!\" (Extended Mix) \u2013 4:59\n#\"Word Up!\" (Instrumental) \u2013 3:05\n\n=== Chart performance ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n! Chart (2014)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|45|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|65|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Czech Republic|92|year=2014|week=14}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Denmark|38|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|107|song=Word Up!|artist=Little Mix}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Irish|13|year=2014|week=12}}\n|-\n{{singlec