{"title_page": "Mad Love (TV series)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Mad Love\n| image                = MadLoveTitle.jpeg\n| show_name_2          = ''True Love''\n| genre                = [[Sitcom]]\n| creator              = Matt Tarses\n| developer            = \n| writer               = \n| director             = \n| creative_director    = \n| starring             = {{Plain list|\n*[[Jason Biggs]]\n*[[Sarah Chalke]]\n*[[Judy Greer]]\n*[[Tyler Labine]]\n}}\n| narrated             = Tyler Labine\n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = \n| endtheme             = \n| composer             = [[John Swihart]]\n| country              = United States\n| language             = English\n| num_seasons          = 1\n| num_episodes         = 13\n| executive_producer   = {{Plain list|\n*[[Jamie Tarses]]\n*Matt Tarses\n}}\n| producer             = \n| editor               = \n| location             = \n| cinematography       = \n| camera               = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multi-camera]]\n| runtime              = 22 minutes\n| company              = {{Plain list|\n*Two Soups Productions\n*FanFare Productions\n*[[CBS Television Studios]]\n*[[Sony Pictures Television]]\n}}\n| distributor          = {{Plain list|\n*[[CBS Television Distribution]] (USA)\n*Sony Pictures Television (non-USA)\n}}\n| network              = [[CBS]]\n| picture_format       = \n| audio_format         = \n| first_aired          = {{start date|2011|2|14}}\n| last_aired           = {{end date|2011|5|16}}\n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| related              = \n| website              = \n| production_website   = \n}}\n\n'''''Mad Love''''' is an American [[sitcom]] television series created by Matt Tarses, that aired on [[CBS]] from February 14 to May 16, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Pavan -- SitcomsOnline.com |url=http://blog.sitcomsonline.com/2011/01/natpe-2011-day-2-has-original-sitcoms.html |title=NATPE 2011: Day 2 Has Original Sitcoms; CBS Moves Up Mad Love Premiere - SitcomsOnline.com News Blog |publisher=Blog.sitcomsonline.com |date=2011-01-25 |accessdate=2014-03-19}}</ref> The sitcom was planned as a [[mid-season replacement]] during the 2010\u201311 television season.<ref name=VarJun3>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118020197.html?categoryid=4027&cs=1&nid=2562 |title=More 'Mad Love' for CBS |date=June 3, 2010 |last=Schneider |first=Michael |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5qpko2zd2?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118020197.html?categoryid=4027&cs=1&nid=2562 |archivedate=June 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2011, ''Mad Love'' was cancelled by CBS after one season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/05/15/the-defenders-s-my-dad-says-and-mad-love-canceled-by-cbs/92704/ |title=The Defenders Cancelled by CBS; $#*! My Dad Says Cancelled by CBS; Mad Love Cancelled by CBS - Ratings &#124; TVbytheNumbers |publisher=Tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com |date=2011-05-15 |accessdate=2014-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nKate, Connie, Larry, and Ben are [[New York City|New Yorker]] thirtysomethings searching for love in the city.  When Kate and Ben meet and fall for each other, their friends remain cynical about the relationship.  Each episode ends with some of the characters in a bar which they frequent, discussing the events of the day.\n\nThe cast describes the show as one about two couples falling in love in very different ways.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n\n===Main===\n*[[Jason Biggs]] as Ben Parr\n*[[Sarah Chalke]] as Kate Swanson\n*[[Judy Greer]] as Connie Grabowski\n*[[Tyler Labine]] as Larry Munsch\n\n===Recurring===\n*[[Sarah Wright]] as Tiffany McDermott, a rich trophy wife and Connie's employer.\n*[[Martin Starr]] as Clyde, Connie's creepy neighbor.\n*[[Chris Parnell]] as Dennis Barrett, a state trooper and Connie's short-term boyfriend.\n\n==Development and production==\nIn September 2009, creator Matt Tarses received a new [[Television pilot|pilot]] commitment from CBS,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2009/09/14/development-update-monday-september-14/8294/|title=Development Update: Monday, September 14|date=September 14, 2009|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> and the network [[Green-light|green-lit]] the pilot in January 2010 under the original title ''True Love''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/fox-cbs-pick-pilots-19159|title=Fox, CBS pick up pilots|date=January 5, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> Initial casting announcements begin in February. [[Minka Kelly]] was the first actor cast, to play the role of Kate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/minka-kelly-falls-true-love-20408|title=Minka Kelly falls for 'True Love' pilot|date=February 8, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> [[Ashley Austin Morris]] joined the cast a few days later as Connie, Kate's cousin and best friend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2010/02/11/development-update-thursday-february-11/8523/|title=Development Update: Thursday, February 11|date=February 11, 2010|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn March, Jason Biggs committed to the series to portray Ben.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-briefs.ew.com/2010/03/10/judy-greer-jason-biggs-jerry-oconnell-tv-pilots/|title=Pilots nab Judy Greer, Jason Biggs, Jerry O'Connell|last=Labrecque|first=Jeff |date=March 10, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=June 29, 2010}}</ref> Other casting announcements included Hal Williams, who signed on in early March to play Earl, who works in the observation deck of the Empire State Building where Ben and Kate meet.<ref name=fcMar5>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2010/03/05/development-update-friday-march-5-part-2/8557/|title=Development Update: Friday, March 5|date=March 5, 2010|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> He was expected to narrate the series, but Tyler Labine ultimately performed that function.<ref name=fcMar5/>  [[Dan Fogler]] and Sarah Wright were cast a week later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2010/03/10/development-update-wednesday-march-10/8566/|title=Development Update: Wednesday, March 10|date=March 10, 2010|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref>  Fogler was added to portray Larry, who is Ben's best friend, with Wright playing Tiffany, a woman who hires Connie to work as a nanny for her children.\n\nPrior to filming the pilot, there were several casting changes.<ref name=deadJune4/> At the end of March, Fogler was replaced by Tyler Labine, who was originally offered the role of Larry but turned it down.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2010/03/tyler-labine-finds-true-love-melrose-place-star-moves-on.html|title=Tyler Labine finds 'True Love,' 'Melrose Place' star moves on|last=Porter|first=Rick|date=March 30, 2010|work=[[Zap2it]]|publisher=[[Tribune Media Services]]|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/tyler-labine-joins-cbs-pilot-22116|title=Tyler Labine joins CBS pilot 'True Love'|date=March 29, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> In early April, [[Lizzy Caplan]] signed on to replace Morris as Connie.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2010/04/09/development-update-friday-april-9/8612/|title=Development Update: Friday, April 9|date=April 9, 2010|work=The Futon Critic|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> The pilot episode was directed by [[Pamela Fryman]].<ref name=fcMar5/>\n\nMore casting changes were announced in June. Sarah Chalke joined the cast in the role of Kate, replacing Kelly.<ref name=deadJune4>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/06/sarah-chalke-to-star-in-cbs-mad-love/|title=Sarah Chalke To Star In CBS' 'Mad Love'|date=June 4, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=Deadline.com|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref>  A few days later, CBS placed a 13-episode series order.<ref name=VarJun3/> The order was contingent on producers finding a replacement for Caplan, who had only agreed to guest star in the pilot.<ref name=VarJun3/><ref name=varJun26>{{cite web |url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118020197.html?categoryid=4027&cs=1&nid=2562 |title=Judy Greer finds 'Mad Love' |date=June 26, 2010 |last=Schneider |first=Michael |work=Variety |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5qpkgRh33?url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118021102.html?categoryid=14&cs=1&ref=verttv |archivedate=June 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=deadJun26>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadline.com/2010/06/judy-greer-joins-cbs-comedy-mad-love-which-is-now-a-go-for-a-midseason-run/|title=Judy Greer Joins CBS' Comedy 'Mad Love,' Which Is Now A Go For A Midseason Run|date=June 26, 2010|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|work=Deadline.com|accessdate=June 28, 2010}}</ref> Caplan described filming the ''Mad Love'' pilot as a positive experience, but decided that she preferred and wanted to look for work on shows more similar to her previous series, ''[[Party Down]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/interview-lizzy-caplan-on-the-party-down-cancellation |title=Interview: Lizzy Caplan on the Party Down cancellation |publisher=Hitfix.com |date=2010-07-02 |accessdate=2014-03-19}}</ref> Judy Greer came on board in late June to portray Connie, finalizing the series cast.<ref name=varJun26/><ref name=deadJun26/>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#FF5C7D |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |viewers= |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |Title = Fireworks\n |DirectedBy = [[Pamela Fryman]]\n |WrittenBy = Matt Tarses\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2