{"title_page": "Kepler-1649c", "text_new": "{{Infobox planet|name=Kepler-1649c|discovery_method=Transit|discovered=15/04/2020|discoverer=Kepler spacecraft|single_temperature=est. 234 \u00b1 20 K}}'''Kepler-1649c''' is an [[exoplanet]] orbiting the [[red dwarf]] star Kepler-1649. It is located 300 [[Light-year|light years]] from Earth<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/earth-size-exoplanet-habitable-zone-kepler.html|title=Newfound alien planet may be most Earth-like yet|last=April 2020|first=Mike Wall 15|website=Space.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. In 2020, Jeff Coughlin, the director of [[Search for extraterrestrial intelligence|SETI]]'s K2 Science Office, described it as the most \"similar planet to Earth\" found so far by the [[Kepler space telescope|Kepler Space Telescope]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Georgiou |first1=Aristos |title=Potentially habitable exoplanet that is Earth-like in size and temperature was discovered 300 light-years away |url=https://www.newsweek.com/potentially-habitable-exoplanet-earth-like-size-temperature-300-light-years-away-1498236 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Newsweek |date=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The planet was originally deemed a false positive by Kepler's [https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/KSCI-19115-001.pdf robovetter algorithm]. The [https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/intro.html Kepler False Positive Working Group] published its recovery on April 15, 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Vanderburg|first=Andrew|last2=Rowden|first2=Pamela|last3=Bryson|first3=Steve|last4=Coughlin|first4=Jeffrey|last5=Batalha|first5=Natalie|last6=Collins|first6=Karen A.|last7=Latham|first7=David W.|last8=Mullally|first8=Susan E.|last9=Col\u00f3n|first9=Knicole D.|last10=Henze|first10=Chris|last11=Huang|first11=Chelsea X.|date=2020-04-15|title=A Habitable-zone Earth-sized Planet Rescued from False Positive Status|url=https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.3847/2041-8213/ab84e5|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=893|issue=1|pages=L27|doi=10.3847/2041-8213/ab84e5|issn=2041-8213}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Strickland |first1=Ashley |title=New potentially habitable exoplanet is similar in size and temperature to Earth |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/15/world/kepler-earth-size-exoplanet-discovery-scn/index.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=CNN |date=15 April 2020 |quote=The study published Wednesday in The Astrophysical Journal Letters.}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\n=== Mass and Orbit ===\nThe exoplanet was identified as a rocky planet by [[NASA]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/news/1637/earth-size-habitable-zone-planet-found-hidden-in-early-nasa-kepler-data/|title=Earth-Size, Habitable Zone Planet Found Hidden in Early NASA Kepler Data|website=Exoplanet Exploration: Planets Beyond our Solar System|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and is very similar to [[Earth]] in terms of size, with a radius 1.06 times that of Earth.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamiecartereurope/2020/04/16/long-dead-telescope-detects-most-similar-planet-to-earth-ever-found-in-a-stars-habitable-zone/|title=Long-Dead Telescope Detects \u2018Most Similar Planet To Earth Ever Found\u2019 In A Star\u2019s \u2018Habitable Zone\u2019|last=Carter|first=Jamie|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Kepler-1649c orbits its host star Kepler-1649, an M-Type red dwarf, every 19.5 days.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seti.org/press-release/dedicated-team-scientists-discover-habitable-zone-earth-size-planet-kepler-data|title=Dedicated Team of Scientists Discover Habitable-Zone Earth-Size Planet in Kepler Data|last=McDonald|first=Rebecca|date=15/04/2020|website=Seti Institute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It orbits within the [[habitable zone]] of its star system.\n\n=== Climate ===\nVery little is known of Kepler-1649c's climate. It is estimated <!-- speculated? --> to be a similar temperature as Earth. It receives only 75% of the light from its host star, compared to what Earth receives from the [[Sun]].<ref name=\":1\" /> It is unclear what the composition of Kepler-1649c's [[atmosphere]] is.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Host Star & Neighbouring Planets ===\nKepler-1649 is a type-M red dwarf star estimated to be roughly 1/4 the radius of our Sun.<ref name=\":3\" /> with only two confirmed planets in its orbit, the other being Kepler-1649b.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/exoplanet-catalog/3489/kepler-1649-b/|title=Exoplanet-catalog|website=Exoplanet Exploration: Planets Beyond our Solar System|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Kepler-1649b is similar to [[Venus]] from our own solar system in two ways. First, Kepler-1649b and Venus both have orbits roughly half the radius of the next known planets (Kepler-1649c and Earth respectively). Second, both of them are of similar size.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Habitability ==\nWhile the exoplanet does orbit within its star's habitable zone, due to the lack of information on the exoplanet's atmosphere, it is unclear if Kepler-1649c can sustain liquid water on its surface. As of 2020, no solar flare-ups have yet been observed from the host star; nonetheless, scientists believe that such stars are prone to frequent [[solar flare]] activity, and that such flares may have stripped the exoplanet's atmosphere and hindered the prospect of life.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox planet|name=Kepler-1649c|discovery_method=Transit|discovered=15/04/2020|discoverer=Kepler spacecraft|single_temperature=est. 234 \u00b1 20 K}}'''Kepler-1649c''' is an [[exoplanet]] orbiting the [[red dwarf]] star Kepler-1649. It is located 300 [[Light-year|light years]] from earth<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/earth-size-exoplanet-habitable-zone-kepler.html|title=Newfound alien planet may be most Earth-like yet|last=April 2020|first=Mike Wall 15|website=Space.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. In 2020, Jeff Coughlin, the director of [[Search for extraterrestrial intelligence|SETI]]'s K2 Science Office, described it as the most \"similar planet to Earth\" found so far by the [[Kepler space telescope|Kepler Space Telescope]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Georgiou |first1=Aristos |title=Potentially habitable exoplanet that is Earth-like in size and temperature was discovered 300 light-years away |url=https://www.newsweek.com/potentially-habitable-exoplanet-earth-like-size-temperature-300-light-years-away-1498236 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=Newsweek |date=16 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The planet was originally deemed a false positive by Kepler's [https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/KSCI-19115-001.pdf robovetter algorithm]. The [https://exoplanetarchive.ipac.caltech.edu/docs/intro.html Kepler False Positive Working Group] published its recovery on April 15, 2020.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Vanderburg|first=Andrew|last2=Rowden|first2=Pamela|last3=Bryson|first3=Steve|last4=Coughlin|first4=Jeffrey|last5=Batalha|first5=Natalie|last6=Collins|first6=Karen A.|last7=Latham|first7=David W.|last8=Mullally|first8=Susan E.|last9=Col\u00f3n|first9=Knicole D.|last10=Henze|first10=Chris|last11=Huang|first11=Chelsea X.|date=2020-04-15|title=A Habitable-zone Earth-sized Planet Rescued from False Positive Status|url=https://iopscience.iop.org/article/10.3847/2041-8213/ab84e5|journal=The Astrophysical Journal|volume=893|issue=1|pages=L27|doi=10.3847/2041-8213/ab84e5|issn=2041-8213}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Strickland |first1=Ashley |title=New potentially habitable exoplanet is similar in size and temperature to Earth |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/15/world/kepler-earth-size-exoplanet-discovery-scn/index.html |accessdate=17 April 2020 |work=CNN |date=15 April 2020 |quote=The study published Wednesday in The Astrophysical Journal Letters.}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics ==\n\n=== Mass and Orbit ===\nThe exoplanet was identified as a rocky planet by [[NASA]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/news/1637/earth-size-habitable-zone-planet-found-hidden-in-early-nasa-kepler-data/|title=Earth-Size, Habitable Zone Planet Found Hidden in Early NASA Kepler Data|website=Exoplanet Exploration: Planets Beyond our Solar System|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and is very similar to [[Earth]] in terms of size, with a radius 1.06 times that of Earth.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jamiecartereurope/2020/04/16/long-dead-telescope-detects-most-similar-planet-to-earth-ever-found-in-a-stars-habitable-zone/|title=Long-Dead Telescope Detects \u2018Most Similar Planet To Earth Ever Found\u2019 In A Star\u2019s \u2018Habitable Zone\u2019|last=Carter|first=Jamie|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Kepler-1649c orbits its host star Kepler-1649, an M-Type red dwarf, every 19.5 days.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seti.org/press-release/dedicated-team-scientists-discover-habitable-zone-earth-size-planet-kepler-data|title=Dedicated Team of Scientists Discover Habitable-Zone Earth-Size Planet in Kepler Data|last=McDonald|first=Rebecca|date=15/04/2020|website=Seti Institute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It orbits within the [[habitable zone]] of its star system.\n\n=== Climate ===\nVery little is known of Kepler-1649c's climate. It is estimated <!-- speculated? --> to be a similar temperature as Earth. It receives only 75% of the light from its host star, compared to what Earth receives from the [[Sun]].<ref name=\":1\" /> It is unclear what the composition of Kepler-1649c's [[atmosphere]] is.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Host Star & Neighbouring Planets ===\nKepler-1649 is a type-M red dwarf star estimated to be roughly 1/4 the radius of our Sun.<ref name=\":3\" /> with only two confirmed planets in its orbit, the other being Kepler-1649b.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exoplanets.nasa.gov/exoplanet-catalog/3489/kepler-1649-b/|title=Exoplanet-catalog|website=Exoplanet Exploration: Planets Beyond our Solar System|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Kepler-1649b is similar to [[Venus]] from our own solar system in two ways. First, Kepler-1649b and Venus both have orbits roughly half the radius of the next known planets (Kepler-1649c and Earth respectively). Second, both of them are of similar size.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Habitability ==\nWhile the exoplanet does orbit within its star's habitable zone, due to the lack of information on the exoplanet's atmosphere, it is unclear if Kepler-1649c can sustain liquid water on its surface. As of 2020, no solar flare-ups have yet been observed from the host star; nonetheless, scientists believe that such stars are prone to frequent [[solar flare]] activity, and that such flares may have stripped the exoplanet's atmosphere and hindered the prospect of life.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n", "name_user": "Andrew Kovnat", "label": "safe", "comment": "Capitalization of Earth.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler-1649c"}
{"title_page": "Rake (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Rake\n| image = Rake US title.png\n| alt = Rake US intertitle\n| genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Black comedy]]\n* [[Comedy-drama]]\n* [[Legal drama]]\n}}\n| based_on  = ''[[Rake (Australian TV series)|Rake]]''<br /> by [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]] {{small|(Australian series)}}\n| developer = [[Peter Tolan]]<br />Peter Duncan\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greg Kinnear]]\n* [[John Ortiz]]\n* [[Necar Zadegan]]\n* [[Bojana Novakovic]]\n* [[Tara Summers]]\n* [[Miranda Otto]]\n* Ian Colletti\n}}\n| composer = [[Patric Caird]]\n| country = United States\t\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 1\n| num_episodes = 13\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greg Kinnear]]\n* Ian Collie\n* Lesly Tolan\n* Michael Wimer\n* Peter Duncan\n* [[Peter Tolan]]\n* [[Richard Roxburgh]]\n* [[Sam Raimi]]\n}}\n| camera  = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime  = 42 minutes\n| company  = {{Plainlist|\n* Blow by Blow Productions\n* [[Essential Media and Entertainment]]\n* Fedora Entertainment\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n}}\n| distributor = Sony Pictures Television\n| channel = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| picture_format  = [[720p]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Digital]]\n| first_aired  = {{Start date|2014|1|23}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2014|6|27}}\n| website = http://www.fox.com/rake\n}}\n\n'''''Rake''''' is an American comedy-drama television series that is an adaptation of the Australian series [[Rake (Australian TV series)|of the same name]], both of which are created by [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]]. Duncan served as series producer with, among others, star [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Peter Tolan]], and [[Richard Roxburgh]], on this version for Fedora Entertainment, [[Essential Media and Entertainment|Essential Media]], and [[Sony Pictures Television]]. On May 8, 2013, the series was added to the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network's [[2013\u201314 United States network television schedule|2013\u201314 schedule]] as a mid-season entry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-drama-series-orders-rake-jj-abrams-519607| title=Fox Drama Series Orders: 'Sleepy Hollow,' 'Rake,' 'Gang Related,' 'Almost Human' |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |last2=Rose |first2=Lacey |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 8, 2013 |accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/charm-wins-over-as-rake-remake-secures-slot-at-fox-20130509-2ja68.html |title=Charm wins over as Rake remake secures slot at Fox |last=Ellis |first=Scott |date=May 9, 2013 |work=[[The Age]] |location=Melbourne |accessdate=May 13, 2013}}</ref> The series premiered on January 23, 2014, originally airing Thursdays on the network, before moving to Fridays late in the first season and eventually to Saturdays for the final two episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/03/foxs-rake-moves-to-fridays-thursdays-american-idol-shifts-to-9-pm-paired-with-kitchen-nightmares/ |title=Fox's 'Rake' Moves To Fridays, Thursday's 'American Idol' Shifts To 9 PM, Paired With 'Hell\u2019s Kitchen' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 3, 2014 |accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/01/fox-moves-rake-from-fridays-to-saturday-burn-off-timeslot/250026/ |title=FOX Moves 'Rake' from Fridays to Saturday Burn-Off Timeslot |first=Sara |last=Bibel |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=April 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> On May 7, 2014, Fox canceled the series after one season, but ultimately aired the produced episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/05/07/dads-enlisted-and-surviving-jack-canceled-by-fox/261517/ |title=\u2018Dads,\u2019 \u2018Enlisted\u2019 and \u2018Surviving Jack,\u2019 & \u2018Rake\u2019 Canceled After First Season by FOX - Ratings |first=Amanda |last=Kondolojy |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=May 7, 2014 |accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series follows Keegan Deane, a criminal defense lawyer whose personal problems and self-destructive behavior have him battling wits and owing money to everyone around him, including his ex-wife, judges, an assistant district attorney, his bookie, a brothel owner, and the [[Internal Revenue Service|IRS]].\n\n=={{Anchor|Cast}} Cast and characters==\n* [[Greg Kinnear]] as Keegan Deane, the titular [[Rake (character)|rake]]\n* [[Miranda Otto]] as Maddy Deane, Keegan's ex-wife and a [[psychiatrist]]\n* [[John Ortiz]] as Ben Leon, Keegan's best friend from law school<ref name=\"astanleynyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/arts/television/in-rake-on-fox-greg-kinnear-is-a-smart-neer-do-well.html|title=He's a Train Wreck, but Still Kinda Cute|last=Stanley|first=Alessandra|date=January 23, 2014|work=The New York Times|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Necar Zadegan]] as Scarlet Leon, Ben's wife and an [[Assistant District Attorney|ADA]] for [[Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/rake-tv-review-673680|title=''Rake'': TV Review|last=Goodman|first=Tim|date=January 23, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Bojana Novakovic]] as Michaela \"Mikki\" Partridge, a $500-an-hour prostitute, with whom Keegan develops a romantic interest, who disappears and then turns up as a law student.<ref name=\"astanleynyt\"/>\n* [[Tara Summers]] as Leanne Zander, Keegan's [[secretary|personal assistant]]\n* [[Jeffrey Nordling]] as Bruce Mangan, Maddy Deane's new boyfriend\n* Ian Colletti as Finn Deane, Keegan's teenage son\n* [[Omar Dorsey]] as Roy, Keegan's creditor who routinely beats him on behalf of the [[loan shark]] to whom Deane owes a considerable amount of money. Keegan holds no grudges and the two men are otherwise friendly.<ref name=\"astanleynyt\"/>\n* Anne Gee Byrd as Frances Leon, Ben's mother, who despises Deane\n* [[Cedric Yarbrough]] as Jules, Mikki's flamboyant former [[pimp]]\n* [[Elizabeth Ho]] as Debbie Lee, daughter of a creditor to whom Deane owed money. She has inherited the family business and forces Keegan to rent an apartment her aunt owns in Echo Park and has threatened to have her cousins break his legs if he doesn't pay up.\n* [[Damon Gupton]] as [[Mayor of Los Angeles]] Marcus Barzmann\n* [[Kim Hawthorne]] as Gloria Barzmann\n\n==Production==\nThe early episodes were aired out of order, as the original pilot, written by [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]] and directed by [[Sam Raimi]], had \"an overload of not drama ... but maybe a little sadness,\" according to producer [[Peter Tolan]]. He added, \"[it] worked against the episode. And so we refigured it, sort of toning that down\". The episode originally portrays Keegan Deane ([[Greg Kinnear]]) in an unhealthy mental and physical state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-in-foxs-rake-greg-kinnear-is-bad-but-only-to-a-point|title=Review: In FOX's 'Rake,' Greg Kinnear is bad \u2014 but only to a point|work=HitFix|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |authorlink1=Alan Sepinwall|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nEpisode 13, \"Mammophile\", should be viewed after episode 5, \"Bigamist\", to maintain continuity.\n\n==Critical reception==\n''Rake'' scored 62 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]] based on reviews from 33 critics, indicating \"generally favorable\" reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/rake-2014/critic-reviews|title=Rake (2014) Season 1|work=Metacritic|accessdate=March 9, 2014}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the show a rating of 66%, based on 38 reviews, with the site's consensus stating: \"''Rake'''s smart blend of comedy and drama makes it the perfect vehicle for Greg Kinnear's offbeat charm and dry humor\".<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/rake/s01/</ref>\n\n[[Hank Stuever]] (''[[The Washington Post]]'') gave it a B+ grade, positing that \"''[[House (TV series)|House]]'' comparisons will surely abound, but ''Rake'' is easily one of the more confident network dramas to come our way of late. It's a procedural ... but it's just unorthodox enough to make me eager to see more.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/a-crowded-midseason-a-guide-to-whats-on-tv-this-winter-and-spring/2014/01/02/a12df920-629d-11e3-aa81-e1dab1360323_story.html|title=A crowded mid-season: A guide to what's on TV this winter and spring|work=The Washington Post|last=Stuever|first=Hank|date=January 3, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Mary McNamara stated \"''Rake'' owes more to the increasingly humane tone of family and female-based comedies like ''[[Modern Family]]'' and ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' than ''[[Rescue Me (American TV series)|Rescue Me]]'', which could (fingers crossed) indicate a similar journey to the light for the ever-popular tortured white male.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-rake-review-20140123,0,4192027.story#axzz2rFKRXb8h|title=Endearing Greg Kinnear plays a lovable legal scoundrel in 'Rake'|work=The Los Angeles Times|last=McNamara|first=Mary|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref> Jeff Jensen from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' awarded the series a B grade, stating \"''Rake'' is yet another show that tries to entertain us with a boorish, morally sketchy protagonist. Comparisons have been made to ''House'' or cable drama cads like [[Don Draper]], but it's the differences from the 'Unlikeable Antihero' archetypes of current TV that define the show.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20778990,00.html|title=TV Review: ''Rake''|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Jensen|first=Jeff|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nNot all reviews were favorable: James Poniewozik of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' stated \"You get the sense that the show ... is vacillating. Maybe it wants to be the kind of raw indictment/worship of reckless masculinity we've seen on cable. Or maybe it wants to be a more picaresque version of ''House'', with a little less genius and a little more self-degradation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2014/01/23/tv-tonight-rake|title=Review of Fox's ''Rake''|work=Time|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]''{{'}}s Maureen Ryan said \"Part of the problem is ''Rake's'' diffidence about how bad a guy Keane is supposed to be. He's clearly a raging narcissist, yet the show deflects that aspect of his personality and tries to make him seem a little bit adorable. If we're supposed to fear that the worst aspects of his personality will land him in serious trouble, the tidy resolutions of various story points in the pilot seem to preclude that possibility ... ''Rake'' isn't a bad show, it just doesn't appear to have the courage of its convictions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/rake-review_b_4647475.html|title='Rake' Review: Greg Kinnear As A Lawyer Gone Wrong|last=Ryan|first=Maureen|date=January 23, 2014|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#2D525D |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |prodcode= |viewers= |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = Serial Killer\n| DirectedBy      = [[Sam Raimi]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|23}}\n| ProdCode        = RAK102\n| Viewers         = 6.95<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/24/thursday-final-ratings-the-vampire-diaries-reign-adjusted-down/231817|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Vampire Diaries' & 'American Idol' Adjusted Up; 'Reign' Adjusted Down|work=TV by the Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|date=January 24, 2014|accessdate=January 24, 2014}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Criminal defense attorney Keegan Deane ([[Greg Kinnear]]) tries to balance his personal and professional life. After winning a poker game, he must enter a guilty plea for serial killer Jack Tarrant ([[Peter Stormare]]). At trial, Tarrant contradicts Deane and enters a not-guilty plea, accusing LAPD's Chief of Police Bernie Michaels ([[Bill Smitrovich]]) of being the author of Tarrant's written confessions to nine murders. Deane must sort out the truth, putting him at odds with the city's mayor and those working for him. Outside the trial, Deane totes around a [[Pacific bluefin tuna]] as payment from a client. He attempts to sell it in order to pay on his gambling debt. When the first potential buyer downgrades the quality of the fish and their offer, he refuses to accept the lower offer. He ends up cooking and eating the tuna himself with his friends.\n| LineColor       = 2d525d\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = A Close Shave\n| DirectedBy      = [[Scott Winant]]\n| WrittenBy       = Allison Abner\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|1|30}}\n| ProdCode        = RAK104\n| Viewers         = 5.24<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/01/31/thursday-final-ratings-big-bang-theory-american-idol-the-taste-vampire-diaries-parks-the-millers-elementary-reign/233436|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'Big Bang Theory', 'American Idol', 'The Taste', 'Vampire Diaries', 'Parks & Recreation', 'Two and a Half Men' Adjusted Up; 'The Millers', 'Elementary', & Reign' Adjusted Down|last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 31, 2014|accessdate=January 31, 2014}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Keegan takes the case of three California [[Conservative Mennonites]] who attack an elder who tries to take a woman member back home to Lancaster, Pennsylvania. The three were arrested for attempted murder, but Keegan learns they merely tried to shave off the elder's beard as customary punishment. During the trial, it is revealed the elder did the same to another man who modernized a tractor. The elder simply does not accept the Californians using cell phones and driving delivery vans for their bakery business. The three are sentenced to six months in prison on the lesser charge of assault and reconcile with the victim as per the Amish doctrine of forgiveness.\n\nMeanwhile, without a vehicle, Keegan takes Maddy's advice and uses a service whereby drivers transport non drivers or non car owners where they need to go based on geographical proximity. Thus, he meets Brooke ([[Alexandra Breckenridge]]), an attractive female driver. He is taken with her until she has sex with Ben's father\u2014she has a weakness for older men\u2014at the Leons' recommitment ceremony. The older man suffers a serious stroke, which later proves fatal.\n| LineColor       = 2d525d\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = Cancer\n| DirectedBy      = [[Jon Avnet]]\n| WrittenBy       = Sara Goodman\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|2|6}}\n| ProdCode        = RAK103\n| Viewers         = 4.27<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/02/07/thursday-final-ratings-the-big-bang-theory-american-idol-two-and-a-half-men-the-millers-adjusted-down/235346|title=Thursday Final Ratings: 'The Big Bang Theory', 'American Idol', 'Two and a Half Men' & the Olympics Adjusted Up; 'The Millers' Adjusted Down|last=Bibel|first=Sara|work=TV by the Numbers|date=February 7, 2014|accessdate=February 7, 2014}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = A young mother, Carol Grady ([[Annie Mumolo]]), gets arrested for insurance fraud when she portrays her healthy son as a cancer patient. When Keegan learns she is a gambling addict using the checks to feed it, he tries to tap into the jury's own addictions and sympathies. Outside the trial, Keegan promises his son Finn (Ian Colletti) 