s-dateline-hannibal-hart-of-dixie-adjusted-down/249240/|title=Friday Final Ratings: 'Last Man Standing', 'The Neighbors, 'Dateline' & '20/20' Adjusted Up; 'Hannibal' & 'Hart of Dixie' Adjusted Down & Final Basketball Numbers|last=Bibel|first=Sara|work=TV by the Numbers|date=March 31, 2014|accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Jules, the pimp who first introduced Keegan to Mikki, becomes his newest client. He is accused of assaulting a powerful Hollywood agent, and Keegan cannot find witnesses willing to help Jules. Meanwhile, Maddy punches Finn's teacher and former lover; Scarlet's campaign stalls; and David Potter gets more serious with Mikki.\n| LineColor       = 2d525d\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 11\n| Title           = Remembrance of Taxis Past\n| DirectedBy      = [[Roxann Dawson]]\n| WrittenBy       = Kit Boss\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|4|05}}\n| ProdCode        = RAK112\n| Viewers         = 1.00<ref name=\"Episode1112\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/06/tv-ratings-saturday-dateline-nightline-prime-2020-up-48-hours-steady-rake-finale-hit-low/251449/|title=TV Ratings Saturday: 'Dateline', 'Nightline Prime' & '20/20' Up, '48 Hours' Steady, 'Rake' Finale Hit Low|last=Bibel|first=Sara|work=TV by the Numbers|date=April 6, 2014|accessdate=April 6, 2014}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = Keegan asks California's ex-governor, Mitch Markham, to provide financial and political support for Scarlet's campaign for district attorney. Meanwhile, Keegan is dumbstruck when Maddy enlists Glenn, a well-known campaign consultant, to liven up Scarlet's campaign, and David Potter, Mikki's fianc\u00e9e, becomes Scarlet's staunchest opponent.\n| LineColor       = 2d525d\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 12\n| Title           = A Man's Best Friend\n| DirectedBy      = [[Jeffrey Walker (actor)|Jeffery Walker]]\n| WrittenBy       = Peter Duncan\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|4|05}}\n| ProdCode        = RAK113\n| Viewers         = 1.02<ref name=\"Episode1112\"/>\n| ShortSummary    = A close friend of Keegan's and well-respected doctor is accused of animal cruelty, after an explicit video of him, his wife and his dog gets stolen. Meanwhile, Scarlet and David's campaigns turn ugly when personal information gets leaked to the press; Ben's firm's finances get investigated by the feds; and Maddy renews a relationship with a former girlfriend.\n| LineColor       = 2d525d\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 13\n| Title           = Mammophile\n| DirectedBy      = [[Paul A. Edwards|Paul Edwards]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Sam Catlin]]\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2014|6|27}}\n| ProdCode        = RAK106\n| Viewers         = 1.28<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/06/30/friday-final-ratings-2020-no-adjustment-for-crossbones/277952/|title=Friday Final Ratings: '20/20' & 'What Would You Do?' Adjusted Up; No Adjustment for 'Crossbones' |last=Kondolojy|first=Amanda|work=TV by the Numbers|date=June 30, 2014|accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = A young boy gets to spend the day with Keegan after his father makes a winning bid at an auction. A middle-aged mama's boy can't tell his mother he was arrested for being a [[Voyeur|peeping tom]] and for indecent exposure. ''(Episode 13, \"Mammophile\", should be viewed after episode 5, \"Bigamist\", to maintain continuity.)''\n| LineColor       = 2d525d\n}}\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.fox.com/rake/}}\n* {{IMDb title|2515462|Rake}}\n* {{tv.com show|rake-2013|Rake}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rake (2014 Tv Series}}\n{{Portal bar|Television|California|Greater Los Angeles|United States}}\n[[Category:2010s American comedy-drama television series]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2014 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American television series based on Australian television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American black comedy television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American legal television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fox Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Rake\n| image = Rake US title.png\n| alt = Rake US intertitle\n| genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Black comedy]]\n* [[Comedy-drama]]\n* [[Legal drama]]\n}}\n| based_on  = ''[[Rake (Australian TV series)|Rake]]''<br /> by [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]] {{small|(Australian series)}}\n| developer = [[Peter Tolan]]<br />Peter Duncan\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greg Kinnear]]\n* [[John Ortiz]]\n* [[Necar Zadegan]]\n* [[Bojana Novakovic]]\n* [[Tara Summers]]\n* [[Miranda Otto]]\n* Ian Colletti\n}}\n| composer = [[Patric Caird]]\n| country = United States\t\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 1\n| num_episodes = 13\n| list_episodes = #Episodes\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Greg Kinnear]]\n* Ian Collie\n* Lesly Tolan\n* Michael Wimer\n* Peter Duncan\n* [[Peter Tolan]]\n* [[Richard Roxburgh]]\n* [[Sam Raimi]]\n}}\n| camera  = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime  = 42 minutes\n| company  = {{Plainlist|\n* Blow by Blow Productions\n* [[Essential Media and Entertainment]]\n* Fedora Entertainment\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n}}\n| distributor = Sony Pictures Television\n| channel = [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]\n| picture_format  = [[720p]] ([[16:9]] [[HDTV]])\n| audio_format = [[Dolby Digital]]\n| first_aired  = {{Start date|2014|1|23}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|2014|6|27}}\n| website = http://www.fox.com/rake\n}}\n\n'''''Rake''''' is an American comedy-drama television series that is an adaptation of the Australian series [[Rake (Australian TV series)|of the same name]], both of which are created by [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]]. Duncan served as series producer with, among others, star [[Greg Kinnear]], [[Peter Tolan]], and [[Richard Roxburgh]], on this version for Fedora Entertainment, [[Essential Media and Entertainment|Essential Media]], and [[Sony Pictures Television]]. On May 8, 2013, the series was added to the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network's [[2013\u201314 United States network television schedule|2013\u201314 schedule]] as a mid-season entry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/fox-drama-series-orders-rake-jj-abrams-519607| title=Fox Drama Series Orders: 'Sleepy Hollow,' 'Rake,' 'Gang Related,' 'Almost Human' |last=Goldberg |first=Lesley |last2=Rose |first2=Lacey |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=May 8, 2013 |accessdate=May 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/entertainment/tv-and-radio/charm-wins-over-as-rake-remake-secures-slot-at-fox-20130509-2ja68.html |title=Charm wins over as Rake remake secures slot at Fox |last=Ellis |first=Scott |date=May 9, 2013 |work=[[The Age]] |location=Melbourne |accessdate=May 13, 2013}}</ref> The series premiered on January 23, 2014, originally airing Thursdays on the network, before moving to Fridays late in the first season and eventually to Saturdays for the final two episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/03/foxs-rake-moves-to-fridays-thursdays-american-idol-shifts-to-9-pm-paired-with-kitchen-nightmares/ |title=Fox's 'Rake' Moves To Fridays, Thursday's 'American Idol' Shifts To 9 PM, Paired With 'Hell\u2019s Kitchen' |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=March 3, 2014 |accessdate=March 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/04/01/fox-moves-rake-from-fridays-to-saturday-burn-off-timeslot/250026/ |title=FOX Moves 'Rake' from Fridays to Saturday Burn-Off Timeslot |first=Sara |last=Bibel |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=April 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 29, 2014}}</ref> On May 7, 2014, Fox canceled the series after one season, but ultimately aired the produced episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2014/05/07/dads-enlisted-and-surviving-jack-canceled-by-fox/261517/ |title=\u2018Dads,\u2019 \u2018Enlisted\u2019 and \u2018Surviving Jack,\u2019 & \u2018Rake\u2019 Canceled After First Season by FOX - Ratings |first=Amanda |last=Kondolojy |publisher=[[TV by the Numbers]] |date=May 7, 2014 |accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series follows Keegan Deane, a criminal defense lawyer whose personal problems and self-destructive behavior have him battling wits and owing money to everyone around him, including his ex-wife, judges, an assistant district attorney, his bookie, a brothel owner, and the [[Internal Revenue Service|IRS]].\n\n=={{Anchor|Cast}} Cast and characters==\n* [[Greg Kinnear]] as Keegan Deane, the titular [[Rake (character)|rake]]\n* [[Miranda Otto]] as Maddy Deane, Keegan's ex-wife and a [[psychiatrist]]\n* [[John Ortiz]] as Ben Leon, Keegan's best friend from law school<ref name=\"astanleynyt\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/23/arts/television/in-rake-on-fox-greg-kinnear-is-a-smart-neer-do-well.html|title=He's a Train Wreck, but Still Kinda Cute|last=Stanley|first=Alessandra|date=January 23, 2014|work=The New York Times|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Necar Zadegan]] as Scarlet Leon, Ben's wife and an [[Assistant District Attorney|ADA]] for [[Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/rake-tv-review-673680|title=''Rake'': TV Review|last=Goodman|first=Tim|date=January 23, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Bojana Novakovic]] as Michaela \"Mikki\" Partridge, a $500-an-hour prostitute, with whom Keegan develops a romantic interest, who disappears and then turns up as a law student.<ref name=\"astanleynyt\"/>\n* [[Tara Summers]] as Leanne Zander, Keegan's [[secretary|personal assistant]]\n* [[Jeffrey Nordling]] as Bruce Mangan, Maddy Deane's new boyfriend\n* Ian Colletti as Finn Deane, Keegan's teenage son\n* [[Omar Dorsey]] as Roy, Keegan's creditor who routinely beats him on behalf of the [[loan shark]] to whom Deane owes a considerable amount of money. Keegan holds no grudges and the two men are otherwise friendly.<ref name=\"astanleynyt\"/>\n* Anne Gee Byrd as Frances Leon, Ben's mother, who despises Deane\n* [[Cedric Yarbrough]] as Jules, Mikki's flamboyant former [[pimp]]\n* [[Elizabeth Ho]] as Debbie Lee, daughter of a creditor to whom Deane owed money. She has inherited the family business and forces Keegan to rent an apartment her aunt owns in Echo Park and has threatened to have her cousins break his legs if he doesn't pay up.\n* [[Damon Gupton]] as [[Mayor of Los Angeles]] Marcus Barzmann\n* [[Kim Hawthorne]] as Gloria Barzmann\n\n==Production==\nThe early episodes were aired out of order, as the original pilot, written by [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]] and directed by [[Sam Raimi]], had \"an overload of not drama ... but maybe a little sadness,\" according to producer [[Peter Tolan]]. He added, \"[it] worked against the episode. And so we refigured it, sort of toning that down\". The episode originally portrays Keegan Deane ([[Greg Kinnear]]) in an unhealthy mental and physical state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-in-foxs-rake-greg-kinnear-is-bad-but-only-to-a-point|title=Review: In FOX's 'Rake,' Greg Kinnear is bad \u2014 but only to a point|work=HitFix|last=Sepinwall |first=Alan |authorlink1=Alan Sepinwall|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nEpisode 13, \"Mammophile\", should be viewed after episode 5, \"Bigamist\", to maintain continuity.\n\n==Critical reception==\n''Rake'' scored 62 out of 100 on [[Metacritic]] based on reviews from 33 critics, indicating \"generally favorable\" reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/rake-2014/critic-reviews|title=Rake (2014) Season 1|work=Metacritic|accessdate=March 9, 2014}}</ref> [[Rotten Tomatoes]] gives the show a rating of 66%, based on 38 reviews, with the site's consensus stating: \"''Rake'''s smart blend of comedy and drama makes it the perfect vehicle for Greg Kinnear's offbeat charm and dry humor\".<ref>https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/rake/s01/</ref>\n\n[[Hank Stuever]] (''[[The Washington Post]]'') gave it a B+ grade, positing that \"''[[House (TV series)|House]]'' comparisons will surely abound, but ''Rake'' is easily one of the more confident network dramas to come our way of late. It's a procedural ... but it's just unorthodox enough to make me eager to see more.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/a-crowded-midseason-a-guide-to-whats-on-tv-this-winter-and-spring/2014/01/02/a12df920-629d-11e3-aa81-e1dab1360323_story.html|title=A crowded mid-season: A guide to what's on TV this winter and spring|work=The Washington Post|last=Stuever|first=Hank|date=January 3, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''{{'}} Mary McNamara stated \"''Rake'' owes more to the increasingly humane tone of family and female-based comedies like ''[[Modern Family]]'' and ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' than ''[[Rescue Me (American TV series)|Rescue Me]]'', which could (fingers crossed) indicate a similar journey to the light for the ever-popular tortured white male.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-rake-review-20140123,0,4192027.story#axzz2rFKRXb8h|title=Endearing Greg Kinnear plays a lovable legal scoundrel in 'Rake'|work=The Los Angeles Times|last=McNamara|first=Mary|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref> Jeff Jensen from ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' awarded the series a B grade, stating \"''Rake'' is yet another show that tries to entertain us with a boorish, morally sketchy protagonist. Comparisons have been made to ''House'' or cable drama cads like [[Don Draper]], but it's the differences from the 'Unlikeable Antihero' archetypes of current TV that define the show.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20778990,00.html|title=TV Review: ''Rake''|work=Entertainment Weekly|last=Jensen|first=Jeff|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nNot all reviews were favorable: James Poniewozik of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' stated \"You get the sense that the show ... is vacillating. Maybe it wants to be the kind of raw indictment/worship of reckless masculinity we've seen on cable. Or maybe it wants to be a more picaresque version of ''House'', with a little less genius and a little more self-degradation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2014/01/23/tv-tonight-rake|title=Review of Fox's ''Rake''|work=Time|last=Poniewozik|first=James|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Huffington Post]]''{{'}}s Maureen Ryan said \"Part of the problem is ''Rake's'' diffidence about how bad a guy Keane is supposed to be. He's clearly a raging narcissist, yet the show deflects that aspect of his personality and tries to make him seem a little bit adorable. If we're supposed to fear that the worst aspects of his personality will land him in serious trouble, the tidy resolutions of various story points in the pilot seem to preclude that possibility ... ''Rake'' isn't a bad show, it just doesn't appear to have the courage of its convictions.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/maureen-ryan/rake-review_b_4647475.html|title='Rake' Review: Greg Kinnear As A Lawyer Gone Wrong|last=Ryan|first=Maureen|date=January 23, 2014|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#2D525D |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |prodcode= |viewers= |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = Serial Killer\n| DirectedBy      = [[Sam Raimi]]\n| WrittenBy       = [[Peter Duncan (director)|Peter Duncan]]\n| OriginalAirDate 